cidId": "", "name": "J. A. Caffrey"}, "organization": {"name": "Marshall Space Flight Center", "location": "Redstone Arsenal, Alabama, United States"}}, "id": "80892d07964e45f0ada439bbd13cc812", "userType": "CIVIL", "userId": "30300ef70ef04793beb5697005101a47"}, {"organizationId": "ff293352e05b51ca965411fc94f5e325", "sequence": 4, "submissionId": 20205007103, "meta": {"author": {"orcidId": "", "name": "J. A. Apple"}, "organization": {"name": "Marshall Space Flight Center", "location": "Redstone Arsenal, Alabama, United States"}}, "id": "6d9eccb69993473bb9bb44a4f4f12622", "userType": "CIVIL", "userId": "91651562e34d4ac1ac71d1954e5c6259"}], "stiTypeDetails": "White Paper", "technicalReviewType": "SINGLE_EXPERT", "modified": "2020-11-24T02:24:44.1711970+00:00", "id": 20205007103, "sourceIdentifiers": [], "created": "2020-09-02T13:05:01.1914760+00:00", "center": {"code": "MSFC", "name": "Marshall Space Flight Center", "id": "a589fc1e68af409f9d2214bb08863d11"}, "onlyAbstract": false, "sensitiveInformation": 2, "abstract": "This paper highlights lunar neutron science that can be performed in support of the Artemis 2024 mission within 6 degrees of the lunar south pole. There are two primary science goals: the characterization of the radiation environment,   and secondly, inference of regolith composition including the presence of water. Characterizing the surface radiation   environment is important for risk identification and mitigation during crewed lunar missions. The lunar surface radiation   environment includes a unique neutron contribution. The relative contribution from neutrons is higher outside the shielding effects of Earth\u2019s magnetic field, which the Moon experiences ~25% of its orbit. To evaluate the radiation risk to astronauts at the lunar surface, fast neutron measurements are needed. Neutrons are generated when galactic cosmic  rays  (GCR)  collide with the lunar regolith and provide valuable elemental composition information about the near surface (< 1m). For the characterization of regolith composition, a low   energy   neutron   spectrometer   or   counter   can determine surface composition. This provides ground truth   for   orbital   neutron   data   from   the   Lunar Reconnaissance   Orbiter   and   Lunar   Prospector missions.", "isLessonsLearned": false, "disseminated": "DOCUMENT_AND_METADATA", "publications": [{"submissionId": 20205007103, "id": "8f244bd2f3ec46a49006d062e2208112", "publicationName": "", "publicationDate": "2020-09-08T05:00:00.0000000+00:00"}], "status": "CURATED", "related": [], "downloads": [{"draft": false, "mimetype": "application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.wordprocessingml.document", "name": "20200831_ArtemisWhitePaper_Neutrons_HH_v0.docx", "type": "STI", "links": {"original": "/api/citations/20205007103/downloads/20200831_ArtemisWhitePaper_Neutrons_HH_v0.docx", "pdf": "/api/citations/20205007103/downloads/20200831_ArtemisWhitePaper_Neutrons_HH_v0.docx.pdf", "fulltext": "/api/citations/20205007103/downloads/20200831_ArtemisWhitePaper_Neutrons_HH_v0.docx.txt"}}], "downloadsAvailable": true, "index": "submissions-2022-09-30-06-07"}